 about how we should implement our new feature using Python's builtins (see below). First let me explain what I mean here; ```Python is designed to be flexible enough to handle complex programming languages like C++ or Java as well - but it also offers many other features which make this kind Of course there are exceptions such things as missing functions from some modules etc... But if one wants to write something useful then they must use python! So why not just include all these extra goodies into their own module structure so people don't need to worry too much when writing custom scripts on top? Well first off lets define two classes called _PySide. These will contain everything needed to run pygame : >>> import sys... print "Hello World" #!/usr /bin\pyenv \ --help show version info """ The main purpose behind PySide was to provide support for various aspects including dynamic linking between programs written inside Lua objects via libc, allowing them access directly through shared libraries rather than having to rely solely upon external dependencies at runtime"""

